Cell["Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s check whether E(1/X) is equal to 1/E(X):", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.947903874957654*^9, 
  3.947903909691427*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"adb70a8e-8c33-4977-9868-\
8a46a0704c2d"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"1.", "/", 
  RowBox[{"(", 
   RowBox[{"37.", "/", "9."}], ")"}]}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.947903912024436*^9, 3.947903943362156*^9}},
 CellLabel->
  "In[471]:=",ExpressionUUID->"7c228115-4a30-449e-b1b9-1ec5fa9d6f01"],

Cell[BoxData["0.24324324324324326`"], "Output",
 CellChangeTimes->{3.9479039464092607`*^9},
 CellLabel->
  "Out[471]=",ExpressionUUID->"5a220037-69b3-45d0-89ed-8c93d42ec28e"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell["\<\
This shows clearly that  that E(1/X) is different from 1/(E(X)). Recall that \
E(bX) = bE(X). It is interesting to see that for some transformations T(X) it \
holds that E(T(X)) = T(E(X)), but for some it does not. This reminds us to
be careful when thinking of the implications of transformations.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.947903999109086*^9, 
  3.947904057949665*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"64af5d02-be7b-4b2e-b346-\
c65debf8baea"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[{
